metadata.name: Skravert #192
metadata.description:
‘Skravert’ - Norwegian, verb, past tense. ‘The act of filling an area with lines; to shade an area’.

Skravert is a series of 320 sketches, each capturing the texture and feel of a material residing somewhere between cardboard and woolen rugs. The project is centred around rectangle subdivision and a line drawing algorithm, giving each piece its own unique expression when combined with a selection of 28 different color  palettes.  

Original artwork by perkwerk * made with p5.js * 2021

metadata.name: Fax Abstraction #84
metadata.description:
The work was created from neurally generated with Latent Diffusion pictorial abstractions, which I was inspired by the work of Gerhard Richter.
They were further hybridized in the spirit of pointillism and Yayoi Kusama and the vintage fax art aesthetic.
Therefore, this work is about the friendship of different artistic styles coexisting together : )

Thanks Yulikolay for help in its creation!

metadata.name: Shift #179
metadata.description:
A generative algorithm honing the power of vertical displacement.

How simple may a generative algorithm be while simultaneously staying diverse enough for each art piece to be truly unique? Shift is the result of an exploration into this space, basing its existence on two principles — dissection and vertical shifting. Each variable in this art engine has been meticulously weighted, giving rise to high diversity and the possibility of epic combinations. 

Shift is a series of 888 unique pieces.

############

Display resolution is 1000x1400. Press ’s’ (in live mode) to generate a 6000x8400 hi-res image. This may take a while to generate depending on your hardware.

Original artwork by perkwerk * made with p5.js * 2022

metadata.name: The Likeness of a Flower #15
metadata.description:
And the unseen eyebeam crossed, for the roses
Had the look of flowers that are looked at.
- T.S. Eliot, Four Quartets: Burnt Norton (1936)

This work is an attempt to encapsulate in an algorithm, not the likeness of a flower, but the likeness of a painting of a flower. If, according to a very old definition, art is an imitation of nature, this is an imitation of an imitation – a sort of meta-imitation of nature by means of computer code.

The challenge for this piece was to capture some of the looseness and fluidity of the human hand when holding a brush or a pencil, and reproducing some typical forms of hand-made scribbles, doodles and brush strokes. However, absent the materiality of paint and canvas, everything is simulated here on the base of a very simple resource: circles. Everything you see is built of very many overlapping circles of varying sizes, colors and opacities. It is circles all the way down…

Inspiration for this work comes from a number of expressionist painters, from 20th century classics like Cy Twombly, to the magnificent contemporary work of Philip Maltman: https://www.instagram.com/philipmaltman/

This work is animated.
Controls:
[SPACE] to play/pause
[r] to restart the drawing
[f] to toggle fullscreen
[s] to download capture
[2] to [9] to generate and save a hi-res image at multiples of the original 1000 x 1000 resolution. Please note that rendering at high resolutions can be slow.

Made with the open-source libraries p5.js and chroma.js

metadata.name: warpGrid #27
metadata.description:
warpGrid uses noise fields to subdivide, warp, and color a plane. For each iteration, separate noise fields are used to perform each action. 

Variable features include: canvas framing, background, 11 different color palettes, grid size, cell shape and fit within grid, edge style, and texture. 

Note: some rarer textures take longer to render.

Type "s" to save the image.

metadata.description: I took the photos used to generate the textures and collage in 2017, in the charming village of Lisle sur Tarn (FRANCE). I have largely reframed to extract only areas of patterns that allow, using P5.js to give a technological dimension to these rural photos.

metadata.name: Sigil Magic I #6
metadata.description:
Sigil Magic is personal, creative magic. The magic of chaos, of anarchy, self directed, unconventional. 
Each piece has a magical connection as denoted by one of ten colour palettes, each equally probable: Spirit, Fire, Faith, Water, Light, Earth, Ice, Stone, Metal and Plant.
Each piece has the potential to have design elements in each of eight compass directions. 
Each design element has its own connections - to masculine, feminine and neutral energy, to health, wealth strength and so on, which means there is great nuance of meaning for each complete Sigil. 
If you wish to receive an intuitive reading on a piece you have minted, please dm me on Twitter or Discord - Kusamehewa#5288

metadata.name: Aging and Forgotten #57
metadata.description:
"Aging and Forgotten" is my tribute to the transience of technology and life. In this exhibit, I bring together a collection of discarded technological devices and symbols of aging and death, such as skulls and bones. My goal is to create a powerful commentary on the impermanence of all things and the parallel between the aging of technology and the aging of people. Through the combination of technology and the human, I invite viewers to reflect on their own experiences of aging, loss, and the passage of time. With "Aging and Forgotten," I aim to challenge viewers to consider the impact of our rapidly advancing technology and the ultimate fate of all things, both human and technological.

- look for the gold mode
- press p to export png
- press s to export svg

metadata.name: Origami. #219
metadata.description:
This piece, as suggested by the name, stems from an old art form that came from Japan about 1000 years ago. And has been practiced by people all around the world ever since.

My goal with this piece was to capture the feeling of origami and everything that comes with it, the paper texture, the delicate and often complicated folds, the colors, everything.

- Press [I] for information about your token (rarities, descriptions, etc.)
- Press [E] to open up the export settings, here you can export your token in up to 5000x5000 resolution.
- Press [<-] to show step counters, showing the process of the folds.

--------------------------------------------------

As for features, we have a couple:

Grid size: ranging from 1x1 all the way to 3x4
Color scheme: a total of 7 (possibly 9) color schemes are available.
Background: either dark or light.
Background feature: if your grid is 1x1 you can have background features.
Outlines: if you have outlines, your Origami will be transformed into Kirigami. (this is toggle-able)
